        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our goal is to map the clump G331.372-00.116 at sufficient sensitivity, angular
resolution, and spectral resolution to measure its internal structure, determine the 
core mass function, and kinematics of the cores (velocities, line widths, and
profiles). The best compromise between continuum and line sensitivity, and the availability of
suitable molecular lines, occurs at frequencies near 270 GHz.

Correlator setup:

We allocate 16 spectral windows in dual polarization mode (bandwidth of 234 MHz) 
and position them to
cover several key molecular transitions. Since the single-dish
line widths are typically ~4 km/s, to accurately measure
line widths and line profiles, we require a velocity resolution
of ~0.5 km/s. For the highest priority transitions, therefore, we select a resolution of 0.5 km/s. Setting all the
spectral windows with this resolution produces a data rate higher than 12 MB/s.
In order to prevent this, we use a spectral averaging of 4 in 6 of the spectral
windows that covered other transitions of interest. 

It is important to choose lines that span a range of excitation energies and optical
depths. A critical diagnostic is to choose an optically thick line and its
much optically thinner isotopologue, since chemical effects are minimized.
Thus, we choose a set-up that contains the optically thick transitions
(HCO+ 3-2 and HNC 3-2), as well as the optically thin isotopologue
HC18O+ 3-2. The optically thick lines measure velocities and line widths. For very cold cores, the
deuterated molecule NH2D is strong (e.g., Sanhueza et al. 2013).
Although unexpected, warm gas,will be
probed by the high-excitation
energy or shock-tracing lines of CH3OH, H2CS, SO2, and HC3N.
This spectral setup will result in an aggregate bandwidth of 3.75 GHz, more
than sufficient to detect the continuum emission with high sensitivity.

Imaging:

We require sufficient angular resolution to resolve the size scales of
individual cores (~0.05 pc). For a distance of 5 kpc, the required
angular resolution is 2". Our simulations of ALMA observations show that
this is adequate to measure the core mass function reliably above 1 Msun
for crowded fields, and above 0.2 Msun for well separated cores. 

To cover the extent of the clump requires a 12-point mosaic (see Fig. 4).  
To address our science goals of detecting the 
large-scale continuum and line emission from clump as a whole also requires the inclusion 
of the ACA. From our previous ALMA observations of G0.253+0.016, we have found 
the inclusion of large-scale emission critical to reliably trace the large-scale dust 
continuum and gas motions.


Sensitivity:

We require sufficient sensitivity to detect cores down to ~0.2 Msun.
For cold dust ~15 K, a 0.2 Msun core will have a 267 GHz flux
of 0.4 mJy at the 5 kpc distance of our source. 

From MALT90, we know the brightness temperatures of density-tracing 
species like HCO+ and HNC (1-0) are ~ T_B = 0.5 K in a 38" beam.   
Since the densities are high, especially toward the cores, the 1 mm lines are likely to 
be comparable.  In fact, they are likely to be brighter, since the  single-dish emission
is almost certainly beam-diluted, and the cores will have high densities.
Moreover, in cold, dense clouds the ground state
1-0 transitions are often self-absorbed.  The 1 mm lines, therefore, are likely
to be brighter than 0.5 K.  Indeed,
excitation models suggest that for conservative values of the 
abundances, the core brightness temperatures will be ~ 1 K.    
As a conservative estimate, and since optically thin transitions 
are typically a few times fainter than the main isotopic
lines (~0.2 K), we require ~ 0.06 K for our 3 sigma
line sensitivity. This sensitivity will provide a 
SNR of ~20. for 0.5 K lines, which is required in order to measure line 
profiles accurately to search for infall signatures.

This setup will achieve point-source sensitivities in the continuum of 0.06 mJy, 
yielding 7 sigma detections for 0.2 Msun cores. 
 </prj:justificationText>
